Fish Collection
There are many ways to capture coral reef fishes. The gear and method vary widely depending
on your target species and the structural complexity of the habitat. In this research, we will be
collecting juvenile parrotfishes, adult territorial damselfishes, and venomous lionfish.
Juvenile Parrotfish
Materials
● Large hand nets x 4
● BINKE net
● Mesh bags x 2
● Coolers x 2
● Portable air pumps and tubing x 5
● Field notebook
● GPS
Fish Capture
1. One person enters the water and briefly (max 5 minutes) scans the reef to see if it’s a
suitable site for parrotfish capture. A suitable site includes at least two large schools of
juvenile parrotfish, and a sand/seagrass “funnel” between two heads of coral that you can
herd parrotfish through into the BINKE net.
2. If it’s a suitable site, 3 divers go down at a time with one BINKE net, and each with a
mesh dive bag and two hand nets.
3. Set up the BINKE net: find a location between two heads of coral or any sort of “funnel”
shape and have one diver hold it up and open. Be careful not to damage the coral and
rocks.
4. Locate nearby schools of prey fish and herd them towards the binky net using hand nets.
Position yourself above them and angle your body downwards, like a lionfish hunting.
Swim very slowly and move towards the net. This ensures that the school doesn’t dart
quickly and scatter but still heads towards the net.
5. Once very close to the BINKE net, swim quickly towards the school for a final push to
scare the fish all the way into the BINKE net.
6. The diver on the BINKE net quickly collapses the net around the fish, while one diver
holds the bottom of the net shut so the fish can’t escape from the bottom. The third diver
gathers all the parrotfish in one section of the net to prepare for transfer to a mesh bag.
7. Carefully transfer all captured fish to your mesh bag.
a. The diver holding the parrotfish bunches the opening part of the net tightly while
supporting the back of the net (with all the fish).
b. The other diver prepares the mesh bag to gather the fish. Coming through the
opening of the BINKE net, put the mouth of the mesh bag over both of the other
diver’s hands so that all the fish are in the mesh bag. This involves tightly
grabbing the diver’s wrists to ensure that no parrotfish escape out the net. When
this is done, then the diver with the BINKE net opens their hands and gently

encourages the fish to leave the net and enter the mesh bag by inverting the
BINKE net and waving their hands to shoo them into the bag. Then, the diver
with the BINKE net slowly pulls their hands and the BINKE net back out of the
mesh bag, ensuring that there are no fish left in the net. Throughout this, the diver
with the mesh bag is still grabbing tightly onto the other diver’s wrists to make
sure the parrotfish don’t escape through the net. This is done slowly and carefully
so as to not harm the parrotfish. When all parrotfish are in the mesh bag, the diver
will tightly seal the mesh bag by bunching above the fish. The fish are now ready
to transport to the surface.
c. SLOWLY bring the fish to the surface and hand them to the boat handler.
d. Note that some amount of bycatch is likely. These individuals will be processed
by the boat team member and returned to the reef.
e. Note that this is not an easy procedure and it will take a couple of tries before
being successful. This process is heavily dependent on the site, the number of
parrotfish present, the weather conditions (e.g., currents), and the equipment you
have (mainly the BINKE net).

Adult damselfish
Materials
• Hand nets x 2
o Small–medium frame, fine, knotless mesh
• Short barrier net (optional but recommended)
o ~3–6 m long, small mesh (≤5 mm) for blocking escape routes
• Soft mesh bag
• Coolers x 2
• Portable air pumps and tubing x 2
• Field notebook
• GPS
Fish Capture
Before entering the water
• Confirm target sample size and maximum handling time.
• Select days with good visibility (≥5 m) and low surge—critical for precise net work.
• Assign roles (2 divers minimum):
o Primary capturer
o Blocker / assistant (net placement, safety)

1. Identify a suitable patch reef and territory
• Choose a small, isolated coral patch with sand margins.
• Locate an adult longfin damselfish territory (algal garden, repeated patrols).
• Observe escape routes (crevices, sand gaps).

Why: Adults are highly site-attached; knowing their bolt-holes improves success and reduces
chase time.
2. Plan the capture approach
• Approach slowly and from down-current.
• Decide whether a barrier net is needed:
o Use it if the territory has clear sand exits.
o Skip it in very complex coral to avoid snagging.

3. (Optional) Deploy a short barrier net
1. Place the net across the primary escape corridor, not over live coral.
2. Keep the lead line tight to sand or rubble; avoid gaps.
3. Allow 20–30 seconds for fish to resume normal movement.
4. Position hand nets
• Primary capturer holds the active net slightly ahead and below the fish’s expected path.
• Assistant positions the block net (hand net or barrier net) to close the rear or side.
Key principle: Damselfish flee short distances to shelter—anticipate, don’t chase
5. Initiate the capture
• Make a calm, deliberate advance.
• Use body position, not rapid finning, to guide the fish.
• When the fish bolts:
o Intercept with the active hand net
o Press gently against sand or rubble, not coral

6. Secure the fish
• Once inside the net:
o Close the net opening quickly
o Transfer immediately to a soft mesh bag
• Keep the fish submerged at all times.
Lionfish
Materials
● Large vinyl hand nets x 4
● Lionfish gloves x 2 pairs
● Coolers x 2
● Portable air pumps and tubing x 5
● Field notebook

● GPS
Fish Capture
** Can be done by free diving or by SCUBA. We recommend free diving because it’s quicker **
1. One person enters the water and briefly (max 5 minutes) scans the reef to locate lionfish.
2. If lionfish are present, 3 people enter the water, two holding large vinyl hand nets and one
holding a long net (e.g., lacrosse stick from the boathouse, or any other very long-handled
net to poke into holes).
3. Position yourself near the lionfish and hold a hand net on either side of it.
4. Slowly and carefully move the two hand nets together, capturing the lionfish between
them. Be careful to hold the nets together so that the lionfish don’t escape but be careful
not to get poked through the netting.
5. Carefully transfer captured fish up to the boat handler.
Boat Fish Care Procedure
1. Take fish from diver and bring onto boat.
2. Place fish into a cooler, separated by species, with at least one airstone.
3. Check to see if the fish is the right species. If it is not, place the fish in a separate
cooler/bucket.
4. Give back the equipment to the diver.
5. Ensure the portable air pumps are working and that the cooler is properly aerated and not
too hot.
a. If the fish is not the right size, notify a diver to bring the fish back down to the
reef the next time that they bring something up. In the meantime, place it in a
separate receptacle with the bycatch (if possible).

6. Do a partial water change every 15 minutes.
a. Scoop out some water (being careful of the fish) and replace it with fresh water
from the ocean.

7. Check often for signs of stress/illness.
a. If a fish looks unwell, place it in a separate cooler/bucket to later euthanize the
fish.
b. Do a complete water change of the cooler that the fish was in.
8. Check often for signs of aggression between fish.
a. If fish are overly aggressive, try separating them by putting them in different
coolers if possible.

*** Note down:
● How long the fish are in the coolers on the boat
● How long to travel from the site to dock, and dock to lab
● What fish is captured in what day - when each fish enters the tank.
